lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: And he shall surety me. But for this Lord,

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: Who hath abus'd me as he knowes himselfe,

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: Though yet he neuer harm'd me, heere I quit him.

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: He knowes himselfe my bed he hath defil'd,

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: And at that time he got his wife with childe:

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: Dead though she be, she feeles her yong one kicke:

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: So there's my riddle, one that's dead is quicke,

lines.speaker: Dia.
lines.text: And now behold the meaning.

lines.speaker: Kin.
lines.text: Is there no exorcist

lines.speaker: Kin.
lines.text: Beguiles the truer Office of mine eyes?

lines.speaker: Kin.
lines.text: Is't reall that I see?

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: 'Tis but the shadow of a wife you see,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: The name, and not the thing.

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: No my good Lord,

lines.speaker: Ros.
lines.text: Both, both, O pardon.

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: Oh my good Lord, when I was like this Maid,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: I found you wondrous kinde, there is your Ring,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: And looke you, heeres your letter: this it sayes,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: When from my finger you can get this Ring,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: And is by me with childe, &c. This is done,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: Will you be mine now you are doubly wonne?

lines.speaker: Ros.
lines.text: If she my Liege can make me know this clearly,

lines.speaker: Ros.
lines.text: Ile loue her dearely, euer, euer dearly.

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: If it appeare not plaine, and proue vntrue,

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: Deadly diuorce step betweene me and you.

lines.speaker: Hel.
lines.text: O my deere mother do I see you liuing?

lines.speaker: Laf.
lines.text: Mine eyes smell Onions, I shall weepe anon:

lines.speaker: Laf.
lines.text: Good Tom Drumme lend me a handkercher.

lines.speaker: Laf.
lines.text: So I thanke thee, waite on me home, Ile make sport with

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Let vs from point to point this storie know,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: To make the euen truth in pleasure flow:

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: If thou beest yet a fresh vncropped flower,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Choose thou thy husband, and Ile pay thy dower.

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: For I can guesse, that by thy honest ayde,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Thou keptst a wife her selfe, thy selfe a Maide.

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Of that and all the progresse more and lesse,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: Resoluedly more leasure shall expresse:

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: All yet seemes well, and if it end so meete,

lines.speaker: King.
lines.text: The bitter past, more welcome is the sweet.
THe Kings a Begger, now the Play is done,
All is well ended, if this suite be wonne,
That you expresse Content: which we will pay,
With strife to please you, day exceeding day:
Ours be your patience then, and yours our parts,
Your gentle hands lend vs, and take our hearts.
